---

## 1. Background

Cline Bot Inc. has launched **ClinePass**, a paid subscription tier
(`$4.99` first month, `then $9.99/mo`) that bundles access to ten open-weight
models from six labs into a single Cline-native "provider":

| Model          | Lab         | Stated purpose                                  |
|----------------|-------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| GLM 5.2        | Z.ai        | Deep reasoning                                   |
| Kimi K2.7 Code | Moonshot AI | Coding tasks                                     |
| Kimi K2.6      | Moonshot AI | Agentic workflows                                |
| DeepSeek V4 Pro| DeepSeek    | Large changes                                    |
| DeepSeek V4 Flash| DeepSeek  | Fast iteration                                   |
| MiniMax M3      | MiniMax    | General coding                                   |
| MiMo V2.5 Pro   | MiMo       | Pro workloads                                    |
| MiMo V2.5       | MiMo       | Efficient edits                                  |
| Qwen3.7-Max     | Qwen       | Heavy workloads                                  |
| Qwen3.7-Plus    | Qwen       | Balanced coding                                  |

The ClinePass FAQ states: *"you can use ClinePass with other coding agents by
using your ClinePass API key."* — i.e. it is intended to be useable from
third-party harnesses such as `forgecode` and `omniroute`.

`cline/cline`'s own README already supports "any OpenAI-compatible API" as a
provider, so adding a new gateway-shaped OpenAI-compatible provider is a known
pattern in the ecosystem.

### 1.1 What is NOT in the public spec

For the avoidance of doubt, the public `https://cline.bot/cline-pass` page does
**not** document:

1. The **base URL** the ClinePass key should be issued against
   (e.g. `https://api.cline.bot` / `https://api.clinepass.ai` / `https://api.cline.dev` / unknown).
2. The **API key issuance flow** for third-party agents (the FAQ references
   "your ClinePass API key" but does not link to a generation surface beyond
   `https://app.cline.bot/dashboard/subscription`).
3. The **wire protocol** — OpenAI-compatible chat completions, OpenAI Responses,
   Anthropic-compatible Messages, or some Cline-native shape.
4. The **model-id namespace** as it appears at the ClinePass provider
   (passthrough like `zai/glm-5.2`, namespaced like `cline:glm-5.2`,
   alias-mapped like `cline-pass/balanced`, …).
5. Whether the same key that works in Cline IDE/CLI works in third-party
   harnesses or is a separate "agent key".

These five items are the **open-questions section** of every upstream-facing
artifact that would flow from this design.

